Author: TonyL#3577
Content:
Trying to optimise warriors scanner - can't understand one moment:

If I do one RPC call per token from tokenlist (just call for each token `cclib playerinfo`) scanning taking 0.11 seconds
When I'm adding second call to check `tokenbalance deadpubkey`  process taking 20 seconds

Author: TonyL#3577
Content: x2 RPC calls = x200 execution time ü§ï

Author: TonyL#3577
TonyL#3577
Content:
If not check ```           elif rpc_connection.tokenbalance(player_info["player"]["tokenid"], "02deaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddead")["balance"] == 1:
                pass``` it's 200 times faster üòÉ

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: do you do them in alternating order?

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: or all playerinfo calls, followed by check dead calls

Author: TonyL#3577
Content: If I'm getting "error" from playerinfo I'm not doing anything else with this token from list anymore

Author: TonyL#3577
Content: And proceed to the next

Author: TonyL#3577
Content: If playerinfo return not error I'm checking tokenbalance on deadpubkey

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: it can be that you run out of memory, so try to do all playerinfo, then issue the dead check all at once

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: yes, so skip the dead check on the first pass

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: that finishes in 0.11 seconds

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: so then it becomes how long does all the dead checks take

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: performance issues often dont fit the normal logics

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: it is all about fitting in to available RAM, or L1 cache

Author: TonyL#3577
Content: Will try to separate this way, thanks for advice!

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: in general if you do X that takes n seconds and Y that does m seconds, it should both take n+m

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: but if you change it so you are doing a bunch of xy things, even though total done is identical, the timing is entirely different

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: like making a sandwich and delivering it to someone across town, and repeating it 200 times

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: vs. making 200 sandwiches and delivering them one by one, but only across the city and back

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: can be indeed 100x faster

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: you would never think to make a sandwich, deliver cross town, come back and repeat

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: as the whole delivery time is very noticeable

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: when issue DB calls, if it incurs a HDD seek... that is milliseconds (cross town)

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: and HDD are smart enough to do things out of request order in optimal ways, of course SSD will reduce this effect, but still SSD is orders of magnitude slower than RAM

Author: TonyL#3577
Content: Have sense, nice example with sandwich üòÉ

Author: TonyL#3577
Content: Python interpreter may also decide that you need barbecue instead of sandwich - faced it when played with python threading

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: oh, there is a "smart" layer in between. then anything can happen

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: the only thing that you would know for sure are specific performance results with specific data sets on specific hardware

```token_balance(rpc_connection, "babe44e3bc746b976f02906a2317234ab583e863b0304a444c1cb606adf6be5c", "02deaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddeaddead")
--- 0.25556230545043945 seconds ---```

Content: For single `playerinfo` call I'm getting response *much* faster than for single `tokenbalance` call
